The Police Service of Northern Ireland (PSNI) issued a brief comment on its engagement at the scene. It said: “Police are currently in attendance at a sudden death in the Kennedy Square area of Downpatrick. “There are no further details at this time.” It was asked to respond to a “medical incident at a private address”. A spokesperson, quoted in BelfastLive, said: “NIAS dispatched two Emergency Crews, two Officers and the Charity Air Ambulance with HEMS on board were also in attendance.” The air ambulance could be seen at the Downpatrick Presbyterian Church. READ MORE: Putin pundit demands ‘Kyiv regime be wiped off face of the earth' It added members were “praying for those neighbours they have come to help”. Users of the Facebook page similarly expressed their concern for the affected. SDLP south Down candidate Colin McGrath said the “while community is in shock”. DON'T MISS: Boris urged to cut the ‘soundbites’ and focus on action [OPINION] Tory civil war erupts as Scottish Conservatives REFUSE to back Boris [REPORT] Prince Andrew legal settlement with Giuffre 'will have been millions' [REVEAL] “Losing a loved one is always a terribly painful experience and I can’t imagine what they are going through at this difficult time. “I would ask that people respect this family’s privacy as they come to terms with their unimaginable loss. “I’m sure the local community in Downpatrick will come together, rally around them and provide support in the weeks and months ahead.”